1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,450
Let me share with you an example of why we must have long-run goals to achieve real success.

2
00:00:06,800 --> 00:00:12,931
Just last week, a young man, let me call him F.B., came to me with a career problem.

3
00:00:13,280 --> 00:00:16,371
F.B. looked well-mannered and intelligent.

4
00:00:16,481 --> 00:00:20,210
He was single and had finished college four years ago.

5
00:00:20,960 --> 00:00:27,731
We talked for a while about what he was doing now, his education, his aptitudes, and general background.

6
00:00:27,920 --> 00:00:32,770
Then I said to him, you came to see me for help on making a job change.

7
00:00:32,960 --> 00:00:35,011
What kind of job are you looking for?

8
00:00:35,360 --> 00:00:38,851
Well, he said, that's what I came to see you about.

9
00:00:39,041 --> 00:00:41,170
I don't know what I want to do.

10
00:00:42,321 --> 00:00:45,170
His problem, of course, was a very common one.

11
00:00:45,280 --> 00:00:52,610
But I realized that just to arrange for the young man to have interviews with several possible employers would not help him.

12
00:00:53,120 --> 00:00:57,011
Trial and error is a pretty poor way to select a career.

13
00:00:57,360 --> 00:01:04,131
With dozens of career possibilities, the odds of stumbling into the right choice are several dozen to one.

14
00:01:04,640 --> 00:01:10,531
I knew I had to help F.B. see that before he starts going someplace career-wise,

15
00:01:10,640 --> 00:01:13,490
he's got to know where that someplace is.

16
00:01:13,680 --> 00:01:17,811
So I said, let's look at your career plan from this angle.

17
00:01:17,920 --> 00:01:22,371
Will you describe for me your image of yourself ten years from now?

18
00:01:22,960 --> 00:01:30,930
F.B., obviously studying the question, finally said, well, I guess I want what just about everyone else wants,

19
00:01:31,200 --> 00:01:34,211
a good job that pays well and a nice home.

20
00:01:34,640 --> 00:01:39,011
Really, though, he continued, I haven't given it too much thought.

21
00:01:39,760 --> 00:01:42,531
This, I assured him, was quite natural.

22
00:01:42,721 --> 00:01:49,731
I went on to explain that his approach to selecting a career was like going to an airline ticket counter and saying,

23
00:01:49,760 --> 00:01:51,091
give me a ticket.

24
00:01:51,281 --> 00:01:56,370
The people selling the tickets just can't help you, unless you give them a destination.

25
00:01:56,481 --> 00:02:02,531
So I said, and I can't help you find a job until I know what your destination is,

26
00:02:02,640 --> 00:02:05,091
and only you can tell me that.

27
00:02:05,521 --> 00:02:07,810
This jarred F.B. into thinking.

28
00:02:07,920 --> 00:02:10,691
We spent the next two hours not talking about the merits of different kinds of jobs,
